Quick.summary: This site was quick to connect and deliver initial code. It began rendering content with considerable delay. The largest contentful paint time was  slower than ideal.

opportunities.title: This test had a reasonably quick first-byte time.
opportunities.desc: A fast time to first byte is essential for delivering assets quickly.

opportunities.title: Zero render-blocking JavaScript files found.
opportunities.desc: Great job. Fewer render-blocking requests mean the browser can visibly render content sooner.

opportunities.title: Zero render-blocking CSS files found.
opportunities.desc: Great job. Fewer render-blocking requests mean the browser can visibly render content sooner.

opportunities.title: Largest Contentful Paint is high (over 2.5s).
opportunities.desc: The element driving your LCP is an image. Some optimizations can help that image fetch earlier.

experiments.title: Preload LCP Image
experiments.desc: This experiment adds a <link rel="preload" as="image" href="//cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/230228084752-02-student-debt-relief-rally-022823-large-tease.jpg"> to the head of your HTML document, causing browsers to request the image earlier and at a higher priority than it otherwise might.

experiments.title: Add Priority Hint
experiments.desc: (Chromium-only) This experiment adds an fetchpriority="high" attribute to your LCP image, causing it to request earlier at a higher priority.

opportunities.title: Zero render-critical images are lazy-loaded.
opportunities.desc: When images are lazy-loaded using loading="lazy", they will be requested after the layout is established, which is too late for images in the critical window.

opportunities.title: Images outside the critical viewport can be lazy-loaded.
opportunities.desc: When images are lazy-loaded using loading="lazy", when they scroll into the viewport, freeing up early load for other tasks.

experiments.title: Add loading="lazy" to images
experiments.desc: This experiment adds loading="lazy" attributes to images that are outside the viewport at load.

opportunities.title: Several fonts are loaded with settings that hide text while they are loading.
opportunities.desc: When fonts are loaded with default display settings, like font-display="block", browsers will hide text entirely for several seconds instead of showing text with a fallback font.

experiments.title: Add font-display: swap
experiments.desc: This experiment adds font-display="swap" to custom fonts to show text sooner.

opportunities.title: 7 fonts are hosted on 3rd-party hosts
opportunities.desc: Fonts on 3rd party domains may take longer to load due to DNS and connection steps that are not necessary when fonts are hosted on the same domain.

experiments.title: Self-Host 3rd Party Files
experiments.desc: This experiment will fetch specified files server-side and reference them on the same domain. Note: the overrides happen at the host level, so any requests from that host will now be self-hosted.

experiments.title: Preconnect 3rd Party Hosts
experiments.desc: This experiment will add a link with rel="preconnect" for specified hosts, which saves time for those steps when the resource is later requested.

experiments.title: Preload 3rd Party Files
experiments.desc: This experiment will add a link with rel="preload" for specified hosts, causing the browser to fetch the file early and at a high priority.

experiments.title: Make Fonts Timeout
experiments.desc: This experiment directs specified hosts to WebPageTest's blackhole server, which will hang indefinitely until timing out. Use this experiment to test your site's ability to display fallback text if fonts do not load quickly.

opportunities.title: Zero unused preloads were found.
opportunities.desc: Preloaded resources are fetched at a high priority, delaying the arrival of other resources in the page. In the case where a preloaded resource is never actually used by the page, that means potentially critical requests will be delayed, slowing down the initial loading of your site.

opportunities.title: 47 files were hosted without using a CDN.
opportunities.desc: A Content Delivery Network (CDN) distributes a website's files throughout the world, reducing request latency. These files do not use a CDN:

opportunities.title: 121 static files have inadequate cache settings.
opportunities.desc: Cache settings can instruct browsers and intermediaries to store recent versions of a site's static files  (JavaScript, CSS, Images, fonts...) for reuse, reducing page weight and latency.

opportunities.title: 171 requests are resulting in an HTTP redirect.
opportunities.desc: HTTP redirects can result in additional DNS resolution, TCP connection and HTTPS negotiation times, making them very costly for performance, particularly on high latency networks.

opportunities.title: Final HTML (DOM) size is significantly larger than initially delivered HTML (747.77kb larger, or 39.2% of total HTML).
opportunities.desc: Typically this is due to over-reliance on JavaScript for generating content, but increases can also happen as a result of browsers normalizing HTML structure as well. When critical HTML content is generated with JavaScript in the browser, several performance bottlenecks can arise:
examples: Before content can be generated client-side, the browser must first parse, evaluate, and sometimes also request JavaScript over the network. These steps occur after the HTML is initially delivered, and can incur long delays depending on the device.
If the generated HTML contains references to external assets (images for example), the browser will not be able to discover and request them as early as desired.

experiments.title: Mimic Pre-rendered HTML
experiments.desc: This experiment mimics server-generated HTML by swapping the initial HTML with the fully rendered HTML from this test run. Note: this will very likely break site behavior, but is potentially useful for comparing early metrics and assessing whether moving logic to the server is worth the effort.

experiments.title: Disable Scripts
experiments.desc: This experiment makes all scripts (inline and external) unrecognizable as javascript by the browser in order to demonstrate whether the site will still be usable if JavaScript fails to properly run.

experiments.title: Make Scripts Timeout
experiments.desc: This experiment directs specified requests to WebPageTest's blackhole server, which will hang indefinitely until timing out. Use this experiment to test your site's ability to serve content if these services hang.

experiments.title: Block Script Requests
experiments.desc: This experiment causes specified requests to fail immediately. Use this experiment to test your site's ability to serve content if these services are unavailable.

Custom.summary: Use this section to create custom experiments to add to your test.

opportunities.title: Add HTML to document
opportunities.desc: These experiments allow you to add arbitrary html to a page, which can for example, enable to you test the impact of adding scripts, 3rd-party tags, or resource hints.

experiments.title: Add HTML to start of head
experiments.desc: This experiment adds arbitrary HTML text to the start of the head of the tested website.

experiments.title: Add HTML to end of head
experiments.desc: This experiment adds arbitrary HTML text to the end of the head of the tested website.

experiments.title: Add HTML to end of body
experiments.desc: This experiment adds arbitrary HTML text to the end of the body of the tested website.

opportunities.title: Find and Replace Text
opportunities.desc: This experiment allows you to find and replace arbitrary text or html in a request.

experiments.title: Find/Replace Text
experiments.desc: This experiment will find and replace occurrences of text in the page, with the option of using regular expressions, capturing parentheses, and flags as well

opportunities.title: Delivery Optimizations
opportunities.desc: These experiments allow you change attributes and manipulate how assets are delivered. Note expected syntax examples when using.

experiments.title: Defer Render-Blocking Scripts
experiments.desc: This experiment adds a defer attribute to render-blocking scripts, causing the browser to fetch them in parallel while showing the page. Deferred scripts still execute in the order they are defined in source.

experiments.title: Async Blocking Scripts
experiments.desc: This experiment adds a async attribute to render-blocking scripts, causing the browser to fetch them in parallel while showing the page. Async scripts are not guaranteed to execute in the order they are defined in source.

experiments.title: Disable JavaScript
experiments.desc: This experiment effectively disables JavaScript (and enables noscript elements) to test a site's JavaScript dependence. It works by changing script elements into scrapt elements, and noscript elements into noscrapt elements so that the page weight remains and behaviors mimic a JS-disabled environment.

experiments.title: Load CSS Async
experiments.desc: This experiment loads specified stylesheets in a way that allows the page to begin rendering while they are still loading. Note that this may cause a flash of unstyled content.

experiments.title: Add Image Aspect Ratio
experiments.desc: This experiment adds width="..." and height="..." attributes to specified images, matching their natural width and height, to provide an aspect ratio.

experiments.title: Inline External Files
experiments.desc: This experiment embeds the contents of specified external scripts or stylesheets directly into the HTML. This increases the size of the HTML, but can often allow page page to display sooner by avoiding server round trips. Note: The inline experiment may break relative references to images and other assets inside the file. These would need proper path changes or absolute URLs in production.

experiments.title: Preload Files
experiments.desc: This experiment adds a <link rel="preload" type="image" href="..."> to the head of your HTML document, causing browsers to request a file earlier and at a higher priority than they otherwise might.

experiments.title: Remove Preloads
experiments.desc: This experiment removes specified unused preloads from the page, allowing other critical resources to be requested earlier.

experiments.title: Preconnect Domains
experiments.desc: This experiment will add a link with rel="preconnect" for specified hosts, which saves time for those steps when the resource is later requested.

experiments.title: Lazy Load Images
experiments.desc: This experiment adds loading="lazy" attributes to specified images.

experiments.title: Remove Lazy Loading
experiments.desc: This experiment removes loading="lazy" attributes from specified images.

experiments.title: Minify CSS
experiments.desc: This experiment removes whitespace from same-domain CSS files.

experiments.title: Add Priority Hint
experiments.desc: (Chromium-only) This experiment adds an fetchpriority="high" attribute to specified images, causing them to request earlier at a higher priority.

experiments.title: Remove Priority Hint
experiments.desc: (Chrome-only) This experiment removes an existing fetchpriority attribute to specified images, causing them to request at their default priority.

experiments.title: Add font-display: swap
experiments.desc: This experiment changes the way a custom font loads so that text can appear while fonts are loading

experiments.title: Make Hosts Timeout
experiments.desc: This experiment directs specified hosts to WebPageTest's blackhole server, which will hang indefinitely until timing out. Use this experiment to test your site's ability to serve content if these services hang.

experiments.title: Block Requests
experiments.desc: This experiment causes specified requests to fail immediately. Use this experiment to test your site's ability to serve content if these services are unavailable.

experiments.title: Self-Host Requests
experiments.desc: This experiment will fetch these requests server-side and reference them on the same domain. Note: the overrides happen at the host level, so any requests from that host will now be self-hosted.
